, UCL
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The Venice variations : Interactions between generation and explanation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
1 Role of spatial analysis considerations in Design and Architectural Knowledge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Architecture and its narrative approach are direct consequences of the geometric
 spatial configuration and an embodied experience, which can be approximated
 through a topological description of space.
 That's why geometry and topology play both key roles in architectural analysis
 ; they have in fact a strong relationship which form determine most aspects
 of the architectural experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a consequence, a useful tool of investigative modeling can be the try
 of different geometric shapes associated with the same topology.
 In that case, whereas the spatial integration stays the same (since we
 define it in the classic way, with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 places and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{ij}$
\end_inset

 the topological distance from place 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, the mean accessibility to other places : 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{S}=\frac{2}{N\cdot(N-1)}\cdot\sum_{i<j}d_{ij}$
\end_inset

 ) because it depends only of the topological configuration, the visual
 integration differs and is interesting to consider as a design criteria.
 The visual integration can be defined as follows : the architectural structure
 can be considered as a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset P\subset\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the part of the space we work in.
 Then the visual integration of a point is the measure of the visually accessibl
e subset taking into account the architectural obstacles (walls).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in P$
\end_inset

, it is defined as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
[I_{v}(M)=
\backslash
intop_{M'
\backslash
in P 
\backslash
backslash S}{
\backslash
mathbbm{1}_{
\backslash
{M+t 
\backslash
vec{MM'}|t
\backslash
in [0,1]
\backslash
} 
\backslash
cap S = 
\backslash
emptyset} dS}
\backslash
]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such a criteria can also be generalised in 3 dimensions, by discrete superpositi
on of floor layers, or by an analog continuous definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Its use can then play role in the development of architectural knowledge.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "calvino1978invisible"

\end_inset

, 
\noun on
Calvino
\noun default
 explains that imagination can be in fact considered as 
\shape italic
Ars combinatoria
\shape default
, that means finding one good configuration among all possibles.
 In other words, creating is exploring the plurality of words.
 The knowledge can be classified in 4 types : dialectic knowledge (empirical),
 encyclopedic knowledge (to make predictions), analytic knowledge (calculations)
 and creative knowledge (imagination) ; and design is in particular the
 combination of the last two : it joins these two different types of knowledge
 through functionnal aspect and the use of imagination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To go further in the role of computation in design, we can consider the
 work of Smithson in the 70s, and the concept of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Mat-building
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 developped particularly in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "smithson1974recognize"

\end_inset

.
 The important ideas are that architecture and urbanism are closely linked
 to the notion of emergence, and that an only top-down approach is not sufficien
t, a bottom-up approach is also needed, by considerations of evolutionnary
 fields and local relations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That importance of computers in design was later in the 90s confirmed by
 the apparition of evolutionnal design, e.
 g.
 design through genetic algorithm that use given rules of the genetic languages
 to compute new designs.
 That is again a bottom-up approach for which the unpredictability of the
 emerging properties is inherent to the system and its self-organisation.
\end_layout

