\begin_layout Section*

\noun on
Meta Berghauser Pont
\noun default
, TU Delft
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Density, Architecture and the City
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Why study density?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through history, density of cities has always have a great importance.
 As a concrete example, there is evidence of the link between a high density
 of population and health problems in Ansterdam, Jordean at the end of the
 19th century.
 At the same time, regulations to constraint the height of buildings according
 to the street width were taken all over the world (see Paris of 
\noun on
Haussman
\noun default
 for example).
 The promoters of the Garden City took the aspect of a healthier city as
 a main argument.
 In the late 50s, Jacobs proposed (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jac56"

\end_inset

) in opposition to these idealisms a return to a more natural and by consequence
 a more dense city.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Today, density can still be an issue.
 Back to the example of Amsterdam, the global density is too low, as a consequen
ce of an explosion of the urban footprint, and of different relative growths
 of land uses (the proportion of dwellings went bigger).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We could try to give an answer to the question of arguments for or against
 densification, but there are very much pertinent arguments on both side,
 so the really important aspect that appears is the study of density in
 itself, the fact that it has good or bad consequences on some aspects of
 the urban system is in fact an other problem, depending most of the time
 on the particular concrete situation we are in.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Measuring density
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Performance of density
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*

\noun on
Ermal Shpuza
\noun default
, Southern Polytechnic State University
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Interaction between boundary shape and circulation structure in the built
 environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent research work has been oriented towards the study of the mutual effect
 of rules and constraints, in the sense of the relations between the building
 shape and the social organization occupying it.
 These two elements have totally different time longevity, so we can ask
 if it could lead to contradictions between the functionnal aim of an architectu
re and its effective use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That lead to the study of two aspects and the links they have : the boudary
 shape of the building and the contained circulation.
 Circulation system is directly linked to a level of movement, and can be
 taken as a local description of floorplates, whereas the boundaries are
 more a global description.
 Such a study can also be done at the urban scale, by searching the impacts
 of an imposed shape on internal circulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will see here first the pure shape aspect, then the influence of circulation
 on shape, and finally the inverse relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
1 Unique shape approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be useful to first describe the boundary shape in itself, since we
 will interest us later on clustering of shapes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a boundary shape, it is possible to extract a polygonal approximation
 (which can be exact in the case of a polygonal shape, what is the most
 used case for the following studies), and then classify it through the
 classification of the polygon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has been shown ([Missing reference]) that a polygonal shape can be quite
 uniquely put in correspondance with 6 sets of reals numbers, that are,
 if we note, with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 summits of the polygons, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}(s)$
\end_inset

 the set of depth 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 adjacent summits to summit 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}^{j}=\{d(k,a)^{j}|k\in S,a\in A_{i}(k)\}$
\end_inset

, the particular sets 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such a classification of polygonal shapes is the starting point of the following
 work, since we will work on unscaled polygonal shapes, i.e.
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 set of polygonal shape and the equivalence relation on it : 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}:P_{1}\mathcal{R}P_{2}\iff(\exists\alpha\in\mathbb{R}^{*},S_{i}^{j}(P_{1})=\alpha S_{i}^{j}(P_{2}),i=1,2,3,j=1,2)$
\end_inset

 , on the quotient set 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{\mathcal{P}}{\mathcal{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 On the following, when we consider polygonal shapes, it will always be
 on that set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
2 From circulation to shape : the inside-out approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This approach is a modular approach, in the sense that it goes from inside
 to outside.
 The internal space influences the boundary shape.
 A shape can be seen as the result of an equilibrium of constraints, external
 and internal forces.
 That approach is the consideration of the internal forces only, to understand
 the influence of internal constraints (for us the internal circulation)
 on the boundary shapes.
 To do that, we concretely consider measures for these two parameters of
 the built environment and we plot different classes of polygonal shapes
 in the plan among these two measures, in order to try to bring out clustering
 patterns between the shapes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
3 Influence of shape on circulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*

\noun on
Ulrika Karlsson
\noun default
, KTH
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Biotic interferences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This presentation is more on research in pure design than in spatial analysis,
 but is closely linked to it because of the underlying systemic approach
 in the design process.
 It presents a work of integrated design lead by a multi-disciplinary team
 at servo Stockholm and KTH, including researchers from several disciplines
 such as Design, Architecture, Ecology of biodiversity, Composition of built
 materials.
 The project was called hydrophile, in relation to its particular aspects
 that we will see in the following.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Presentation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To define the project in itself, which name is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

biotic interference
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we need to come back to the initial definition of these words : biotic
 means related with living organism, and interference should be taken here
 as the emergence from sharing by agents of a system.
 Here the abstract aim of the project is to create such positives interferences
 within a biotic system.
 It lays on the line of relationship between technical design (mathematical
 aspects) and architecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An ubiquitous idea is the overreaching presence of nature, almost a symbiosis
 between all the dirts of nature and human being, as it can be feeled in
 the introduction sequence of the swedish film 
\shape italic
Melancholia
\shape default
, or in the artwork 
\shape italic
Partially Buried Woodshed
\shape default
 by 
\noun on
Robert Smithson
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the 70s, 
\noun on
Banham
\noun default
 built in Los Angeles the first green roof building, in a exceptionaly innovativ
e way, through the elegant combination of glass walls with the turf roof.
 He was one of the first to propose ecology-oriented analysis of urban systems
 and environmental designed architectural projects.
 He wrote theorical explanations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "banham1984architecture"

\end_inset

.
 One ambitious aim of the project is to reinvent, to rethink that concept
 of green roof, in a innovative approach called the hydrodynamic green roof.
\end_layout

