Algorithmic aspects of spatial analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That last presentation is a short overview of computer science issues that
 occur when doing spatial analysis and investigative modeling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Complexity of algorithms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When doing computations, the speed depends on the machine on which they
 are done, but what is really important is the intrinsic complexity of the
 used algorithm.
 For example, there exists many ways to sort a set of number, and the best
 ones (quick sort or fusion) will have a mean complexity in 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n\cdot ln(n))$
\end_inset

, what can be assimilated to a linear time as a function of the size of
 the set, whereas bad ones will execute in 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n^{2})$
\end_inset

, what is quadratic and can quickly lead to impossible calculation times
 on big data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This aspect is particularly important in spatial analysis because of the
 size of the data and the natural complexity of graph exploration problems,
 that's why finding 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 algorithms for spatial analysis is necessary.
\end_layout

